                <h4 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 8px;">Cat urinary track infection</h4>
                <p> Feline Lower Urinary Tract Disease (FLUTD) is a frustrating syndrome in veterinary medicine, causing discomfort, frequent trips to the litter box, and even death if the urethra becomes completely obstructed. Most cases do not have a readily identifiable cause, but stress is thought to be a trigger. Prompt veterinary care is key to a positive outcome, and cat parents should be aware of the signs of urinary tract disease so they can be evaluated quickly. Symptoms include frequent trips to the litter box, blood in urine, and reliving themselves outside the litter box. In severe cases, the cat may become depressed, unresponsive, or even die. Diagnosis involves examination by a veterinarian, which may recommend tests like urinealysis, x-rays for stones, and bloodwork for severely ill cats. The prognosis for cats without obstruction is fair to good, with uncomplicated cases usually resolving within 5-7 days. For cats with obstruction, the long-term prognosis depends on their health at the time of presentation. Treatment may involve a urinary catheter, often under anesthesia, and perineal urethrostomy if multiple recurrences occur.</p>
            </div>

        </div>
    </section>

